Title:
Bring Your Own Trusted Binary (BYOTB) – BSides Edition

Type:
Blog Post

Short Summary (4–8 sentences max):
- This post summarizes a BSides London 2024 talk on abusing “trusted” third-party binaries (primarily Cloudflare’s `cloudflared` and Win32-OpenSSH) for stealthy tunneling and access in compromised environments.  
- It focuses on using `cloudflared` as an SSH `ProxyCommand` to egress over TCP/443 as HTTPS, enabling reverse port forwards and SOCKS proxies without relying on typical tunneling tools (e.g., Ligolo) and with reduced EDR friction.  
- The author shows how to bring your own `ssh.exe` (plus required DLLs) and optionally deploy `sshd` for persistent command-line access, as well as port-forwarding for scenarios like coercion/NTLM relay workflows.  
- A key section explores Cloudflare WARP + `cloudflared` for tool-native access (e.g., NetExec) and introduces a “double tunnel” technique leveraging an undocumented `edge` feature to avoid outbound port 7844 restrictions by chaining through an Access listener over 443.  
- Defensive guidance is included: process/command-line telemetry, DNS monitoring for `argotunnel.com`, firewall logging/blocks for 7844, and file/download monitoring for `cloudflared` artifacts.  
- Useful for red teams and pentesters building firewall-friendly egress and pivoting paths, and for blue teams looking to detect Cloudflare-tunnel-based tradecraft.

Technical Focus:
- BYOTB / living-off-trusted-binaries (Cloudflare `cloudflared`, Win32-OpenSSH)
- SSH `ProxyCommand`, reverse (`-R`) and local (`-L`) port forwarding, SOCKS proxying
- Cloudflare Tunnel / Access SSH and TCP forwarding over HTTPS (443)
- WARP client as VPN-like access path for operator tooling (e.g., NetExec)
- “Double tunnel” chaining to bypass port 7844 egress constraints (TCP/http2)
- Detection opportunities: process args, DNS (`argotunnel.com`), firewall telemetry, file integrity

Use Cases:
- Establish stealthy egress over 443 using `cloudflared` to carry SSH traffic as HTTPS
- Create SOCKS proxies and port forwards for internal pivoting without custom implants
- Deploy portable OpenSSH (`ssh.exe`/`sshd`) on targets lacking an SSH client
- Forward SMB/HTTP to support relay/coercion workflows (e.g., NTLM relay/RBCD-style paths)
- Operate in restrictive networks by avoiding direct outbound 7844 via chained tunneling
- Build detections for Cloudflare-tunnel abuse via DNS/process/firewall/file monitoring

Keywords:
cloudflared, Cloudflare Tunnel, Cloudflare Access, WARP, BYOTB, trusted binary abuse, SSH ProxyCommand, reverse port forward, local port forward, SOCKS proxy, Proxychains, NetExec, argotunnel.com, port 7844, TCP 443, HTTP/2, Win32-OpenSSH, sshd, NTLM relay, RBCD